    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To achieve Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS), every part of the earthing system must be correctly linked to create a complete path for fault current.",
      "In a TT system, because the supplier provides no earth terminal, the path relies entirely on the consumer's own installation components to reach the mass of earth.",
      "This involves a specific sequence: the internal circuit protection, the main link for the whole building, and the physical connection to the ground itself."
    ],
    "questionText": "A fault occurs in a metal appliance within a rural cottage that utilizes a TT earthing system. Describe the path the fault current takes to reach the ground, specifically naming the conductor within the appliance's circuit, the main conductor connecting the installation to the earth source, and the physical component driven into the soil.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The fault current travels through the Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC) to the Main Earthing Terminal (MET). From the MET, it travels through the Earthing Conductor to the Earth Electrode (or earth rod), which then dissipates the current into the ground."
    ],
    "hint": "Start with the green-and-yellow wire inside the circuit cable, move to the main 'artery' conductor leaving the consumer unit, and end with the metal component located in the ground outside."
